"""
mkt-christ | Leviticus | chapters 16–18
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-leviticus-16-18-fill.py

Ch 16: Yom Kippur — the single most Hebrews-dense chapter in Leviticus:
        two-goat mechanism (chatat + Azazel), linen-humiliation type,
        kapporet blood as Rom 3:25 hilasterion, outside-camp burning as Heb 13:11-12,
        once-per-year restriction as Heb 9:7,25-28 contrast;
        ch 16 v2 already present.
Ch 17: Blood-centralization types; se'irim prohibition as exclusivity of Christ's
        sacrifice; earth-covered blood as burial type; karet for blood-eating reversed
        by John 6:53; ch 17 v11 already present.
Ch 18: Egypt/Canaan third-way type; "live by them" as Gal 3:12 / Rom 10:5 crux;
        land-vomiting curse borne by Christ; covenant-closing formula.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DATA = {
  "16": {
    "1": "<p>After the death of Aaron's two sons when they drew near before YHWH — Yom Kippur's legislation is framed by the deaths of Nadab and Abihu (Lev 10:1-3): unauthorized approach to the most holy place results in death. This death-framing establishes the theological premise for the entire chapter: the problem of human approach to the holy God. Christ answers this problem not by heightening the restriction (as Yom Kippur's annual once-only limitation does) but by permanently resolving it: 'Therefore, brothers, since we have confidence to enter the holy places by the blood of Jesus' (Heb 10:19).</p>",
    "3": "<p>Aaron shall come into the Holy Place with a young bull for a sin offering and a ram for a burnt offering — the high priest enters with specific prescribed animals. Hebrews 7:27 identifies the contrast: 'He has no need, like those high priests, to offer sacrifices daily, first for his own sins and then for those of the people, since he did this once for all when he offered up himself.' Aaron's required bull for his own sins is the type that reveals Christ's superiority: the perfect High Priest needs no personal sin offering because he has no sin to atone for.</p>",
    "4": "<p>He shall put on the holy linen coat and shall have the linen undergarments on his body — on Yom Kippur the high priest strips the gold and jewels and wears only white linen. The voluntary self-reduction to the simplest priestly garments on the day of atonement is the type of Christ's kenosis: 'who, though he was in the form of God, did not count equality with God a thing to be grasped, but emptied himself, taking the form of a servant' (Phil 2:6-7). The glory is not abandoned but veiled; the linen covers the gold as the human nature veils the divine glory.</p>",
    "5": "<p>From the congregation two male goats for a sin offering — the two-goat complex is a single sin offering with a split function: one goat dies, one carries sin away. Together they accomplish what no single sacrifice mechanism can express: the removal of sin's guilt (through death and blood) and the removal of sin's presence (through the carrying-away to the wilderness). Christ fulfills both simultaneously: 'the Lamb of God who takes away (<em>airōn</em>) the sin of the world' (John 1:29) — takes away by bearing and removing, not merely covering.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Aaron shall offer the bull as a sin offering for himself — the high priest atones for himself before atoning for the congregation. Christ inverts this sequence: he has no sin to atone for, so his atoning work is entirely on behalf of others from the first moment. 'For we do not have a high priest who is unable to sympathize with our weaknesses, but one who in every respect has been tempted as we are, yet without sin' (Heb 4:15). The absence of a personal sin offering for Christ is the proof of his priestly perfection.</p>",
    "7": "<p>He shall take the two goats and set them before YHWH at the entrance of the tent of meeting — the two goats presented together as a single offering unit. Christ is the complete fulfillment of both goats simultaneously: his death satisfies divine justice (YHWH-lot goat), and his resurrection carries sin away permanently (Azazel-lot goat). The separation of the two functions in the type is resolved in the single act of the antitype: 'He has appeared once for all at the end of the ages to put away sin by the sacrifice of himself' (Heb 9:26).</p>",
    "8": "<p>One lot for YHWH and one lot for Azazel — the divine determination of which goat fulfills which function. Christ's appointment as the sacrifice was not contingent or accidental: 'this Jesus, delivered up according to the definite plan and foreknowledge of God' (Acts 2:23); 'a lamb without blemish or spot who was foreknown before the foundation of the world' (1 Pet 1:19-20). The lot that falls before YHWH is the type of the eternal election of the Son as both YHWH-lot and Azazel-lot offering.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The goat on which the lot fell for YHWH shall be used as a sin offering — the slaughtered goat, the one offered to YHWH, provides the blood for the sanctuary's purification. Christ's blood is specifically the purifying agent for the heavenly sanctuary: 'it was necessary for the copies of the heavenly things to be purified with these rites, but the heavenly things themselves with better sacrifices than these' (Heb 9:23). The YHWH-lot goat's blood entering the most holy place is the type of Christ's own blood entering the heavenly sanctuary.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The goat on which the lot fell for Azazel shall be presented alive before YHWH to make atonement over it — the Azazel goat is presented alive, not yet sent, while Aaron confesses over it. The living goat bears confession before being sent. Christ also lives — is presented before the Father as the living Lord — while his sacrifice accomplished the bearing-away of sin. 'Christ Jesus is the one who died — more than that, who was raised — who is at the right hand of God, who indeed is interceding for us' (Rom 8:34). He is the Azazel-goat still present, alive, interceding.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Aaron shall present the bull as a sin offering for himself — the second mention of Aaron's personal sin offering. The repetition underlines the contrast with Christ: the Levitical high priest must atone for himself twice (vv.6 and 11); Christ atones for himself zero times. Every mention of Aaron's personal atonement requirement is an implicit pointer to its absence in the perfect High Priest. 'Such a high priest was indeed fitting for us: holy, innocent, unstained, separated from sinners, and exalted above the heavens' (Heb 7:26).</p>",
    "12": "<p>A censer full of coals from the altar and two handfuls of incense to create a cloud covering the mercy seat — the incense protects Aaron from the unveiled divine presence. Christ enters the heavenly most holy place not with incense for protection but with his own blood that gives him free access: 'by the greater and more perfect tent... not by means of the blood of goats and calves but by means of his own blood, he entered once for all into the holy places, securing an eternal redemption' (Heb 9:11-12). The protection the incense provided is rendered unnecessary by the access Christ's blood secured.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The incense cloud shall cover the mercy seat so that Aaron does not die — the protective cloud between the priest and the divine presence. Christ needs no such protection: 'he always lives in the presence of God' (Heb 9:24, <em>emfanisthēnai tō prosōpō tou theou</em> — to appear in the presence of God). The Son who is 'the radiance of the glory of God and the exact imprint of his nature' (Heb 1:3) faces the divine presence directly without mediating cloud.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Some blood of the bull sprinkled on the front of the mercy seat seven times — the blood manipulation on the kapporet. Hebrews 9:7,11-12: 'into the second tent only the high priest goes, and only once a year, and not without blood... Christ entered once for all into the holy places... by means of his own blood, securing an eternal redemption.' Every element of v.14 is explicitly contrasted in Hebrews: Aaron enters with someone else's blood, once a year, for temporary coverage; Christ enters with his own blood, once for all time, for eternal redemption.</p>",
    "15": "<p>He shall kill the goat of the sin offering that is for the people and bring its blood inside the veil — the communal sin offering's blood entering the most holy place. Christ enters the heavenly sanctuary not with the blood of goats but with his own blood as the communal sin offering for all humanity: 'he is the propitiation for our sins, and not for ours only but also for the sins of the whole world' (1 John 2:2). The communal scope of the Yom Kippur goat's blood — covering all Israel — points to the universal scope of Christ's atoning blood.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Atonement for the Holy Place because of the uncleannesses of the people — the sanctuary itself requires annual purification from accumulated human impurity. Christ's sacrifice purifies the conscience from dead works: 'how much more will the blood of Christ, who through the eternal Spirit offered himself without blemish to God, purify our conscience from dead works to serve the living God' (Heb 9:14). The sanctuary-purification of the type becomes the conscience-purification of the antitype.</p>",
    "17": "<p>No one may be in the tent of meeting during the high priest's atoning work — absolute solitude in the most critical priestly moment. In Gethsemane and on the cross, Christ is ultimately alone: 'they all left him and fled' (Mark 14:50); 'My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?' (Mark 15:34). The required solitude of the Yom Kippur high priest is fulfilled in the desolate solitude of the crucified High Priest who bears the full weight of atonement without human support.</p>",
    "18": "<p>He shall go out to the outer altar and put blood from both offerings on its horns — after the inner sanctuary, the outer altar receives blood from both the priestly and communal sin offerings. The mixed blood (bull + goat) on the altar represents the complete covering of both the priestly and lay dimensions of the community's sin. Christ's blood covers the full spectrum: 'This is my blood of the covenant, which is poured out for many for the forgiveness of sins' (Matt 26:28). 'Many' (<em>pollōn</em>) translates the Isa 53:12 <em>rabbim</em> — the comprehensive covenant community.</p>",
    "19": "<p>He shall sprinkle the blood on the outer altar seven times and cleanse and consecrate it — seven sprinklings reconsecrate the altar that has been defiled by the year's accumulated sin. Christ's blood reconsecrates fallen humanity itself: 'you are a chosen race, a royal priesthood, a holy nation, a people for his own possession' (1 Pet 2:9). The altar cleansed and reconsecrated by Yom Kippur blood is the type of the royal priesthood cleansed and consecrated by Christ's blood to serve the living God.</p>",
    "20": "<p>When he has finished atoning for the Holy Place and the tent and the altar, he shall present the live goat — the spatial sequence of atonement ends with the live Azazel goat. After Christ's sacrifice (the YHWH-lot completion), he presents himself alive as the Azazel-dimension: the risen Christ who carries human sin away permanently, seated at the right hand of the Father (Heb 1:3; 10:12). The presentation of the live goat after the atoning work is the type of the resurrection-presentation of the risen Lord who continues to bear and remove sin through his perpetual intercession.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Aaron shall lay both his hands on the head of the live goat and confess all the iniquities and transgressions and sins of Israel — the most explicit sin-bearing act in the OT, preceding Isa 53's language: the full weight of Israel's sin is transferred to the goat through the double-hand gesture and verbal confession. Isaiah 53:6: 'YHWH has laid on him the iniquity of us all' (<em>hifgea bo</em>, caused to fall upon him). 2 Cor 5:21: 'For our sake he made him to be sin who knew no sin.' The Azazel goat's sin-loading is fulfilled in the cross where all human iniquity is laid upon the Son.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The goat shall bear all their iniquities to a remote area and be let go — <em>nasa</em> (bear, carry, remove) is the verb used for the Servant's sin-bearing in Isa 53:4,11,12: 'he has borne our griefs... he bore the sin of many.' The scapegoat going to the remote cut-off land is the type of Christ's 'descent into the lower parts of the earth' (Eph 4:9), bearing sin into the domain of death and abandonment, and of his permanent removal of sin: 'as far as the east is from the west, so far does he remove our transgressions from us' (Ps 103:12).</p>",
    "23": "<p>Aaron shall come into the tent of meeting and take off the linen garments he put on when he went into the Holy Place — after the atonement work is complete, the high priest removes the linen and (v.24) resumes the gold vestments. Christ's humiliation is followed by his exaltation: 'therefore God has highly exalted him and bestowed on him the name that is above every name' (Phil 2:9). The resuming of the regular high-priestly garments after Yom Kippur is the type of the resurrection-glorification: the servant-form of the linen gives way to the royal-form of the gold.</p>",
    "24": "<p>He shall bathe his body in water in a holy place and put on his garments and come out and offer his burnt offering and the burnt offering of the people — the post-atonement purification, change of garments, and resumption of normal priestly ministry. Christ's resurrection is the post-atonement return: he comes out of the tomb having completed the atoning work, resumes his royal-priestly ministry, and presents the burnt offering of his complete consecration to the Father ('it is finished' → the ascension where he presents himself as the final offering, Heb 9:24).</p>",
    "25": "<p>The fat of the sin offerings burned on the altar — even on Yom Kippur the fat belongs to YHWH. The perpetual fat-offering on the altar on the holiest day of the year confirms that what belongs to God cannot be withheld even in the most intensive human atonement act. Christ's life 'poured out' on the cross (Matt 20:28; Phil 2:17: 'poured out as a drink offering') is the total giving of the divine-human richness to the Father, the ultimate fat-offering on the altar of the cross.</p>",
    "26": "<p>He who led the goat to Azazel shall wash his clothes and bathe — the sin-laden goat's handler contracts impurity. The disciples who witnessed the crucifixion — who watched the one bearing all human sin — needed the resurrection to make sense of what they had witnessed; the proximity to the sin-bearing Jesus in his death created a kind of moral-spiritual disorientation that only the resurrection-encounter could 'purify.' Peter's reinstatement (John 21:15-19) is the type of the washing-after-scapegoat-handling that the resurrection provided for those who were near the cross.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The sin offering animals whose blood was brought into the Holy Place shall be burned outside the camp — the outside-camp burning of the most-holy sin offering is the direct type cited in Heb 13:11-13: 'For the bodies of those animals whose blood is brought into the holy places by the high priest as a sacrifice for sin are burned outside the camp. So Jesus also suffered outside the gate in order to sanctify the people through his own blood. Therefore let us go to him outside the camp and bear the reproach he endured.' The type is explicitly applied: Golgotha is the outside-camp burning location of the perfect sin offering.</p>",
    "28": "<p>He who burns them shall wash his clothes and bathe — the contact with the most holy sin offering carcasses creates impurity for the handler, requiring purification. All who participate in Christ's atoning death — all who are baptized into his death (Rom 6:3) — undergo the washing-and-bathing transformation: 'you were washed, you were sanctified, you were justified in the name of the Lord Jesus Christ and by the Spirit of our God' (1 Cor 6:11). The purification required of those who handled the sin offering becomes the washing given to those who come through Christ's death.</p>",
    "29": "<p>On the tenth day of the seventh month you shall afflict yourselves and do no work — Yom Kippur's communal self-affliction creates corporate participation in the high-priestly atonement; the people join the suffering dimension of the high priest's solitary work through their fast. Christ's call to 'deny yourself and take up your cross' (Mark 8:34) extends the Yom Kippur self-affliction pattern into continuous discipleship: the annual fast becomes the daily self-denial of the new covenant community.</p>",
    "30": "<p>On this day atonement shall be made for you to cleanse you — <em>mikal chatoteichem lifney YHWH titharu</em>, from all your sins before YHWH you shall be clean. The comprehensive atonement of Yom Kippur — 'all your sins' — is the type of the total justification provided by Christ: 'there is therefore now no condemnation for those who are in Christ Jesus' (Rom 8:1). The annual declaration of total cleanliness becomes the permanent verdict of justification in Christ: 'God presented him as the one who would turn aside his wrath, taking away sin' (Rom 3:25 NIV).</p>",
    "31": "<p><em>Shabbat shabbaton</em> — the most intense Sabbath rest, the Sabbath of Sabbaths. Yom Kippur's super-Sabbath is the type of the rest secured by Christ's completed atonement: 'whoever has entered God's rest has also rested from his works as God did from his' (Heb 4:10). Christ's 'It is finished' (John 19:30) is the declaration of the ultimate shabbat shabbaton — the rest from the works of atonement, the completed work that creates the basis for the eschatological Sabbath-rest of the people of God.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The anointed priest who serves in his father's place shall perform the atonement — the successor high priest performs the identical ceremony; the rite is perpetuated through the Aaronic succession. Christ's priesthood is not succeeded but permanent: 'he holds his priesthood permanently, because he continues forever' (Heb 7:24). The Levitical succession that required each generation to repeat the atonement is contrasted with the permanent, non-successive priesthood of the Son whose single atonement requires no successor and no repetition.</p>",
    "33": "<p>He shall make atonement for the holy sanctuary, the tent, the altar, the priests, and all the people — the comprehensive four-part atonement: sacred spaces and sacred persons. Christ's atonement covers the full scope of what Yom Kippur addressed and more: 'it was necessary for the copies of the heavenly things to be purified with these rites, but the heavenly things themselves with better sacrifices' (Heb 9:23). The range of what the Levitical atonement covered is precisely the range of what Christ's sacrifice definitively covers — and the heavenly originals beyond.</p>",
    "34": "<p>This shall be a statute forever: once a year atonement shall be made for all the sins of Israel — <em>achat bashanah</em>, once per year. The once-per-year restriction is Hebrews' primary evidence for the inadequacy of the Levitical system and the necessity of Christ's once-for-all sacrifice: 'But when Christ appeared as a high priest of the good things that have come... he entered once for all into the holy places, not by means of the blood of goats and calves but by means of his own blood, securing an eternal redemption' (Heb 9:11-12). Nor is it repeated annually any longer: 'he has appeared once for all at the end of the ages to put away sin by the sacrifice of himself' (Heb 9:26).</p>"
  },
  "17": {
    "1": "<p>YHWH spoke to Moses — the centralization law of ch 17 is covenant-foundational: all slaughter of sacrificial animals must come to the tabernacle. The exclusivity principle encoded here points to Christ's exclusive claim: 'I am the way, and the truth, and the life. No one comes to the Father except through me' (John 14:6). Just as all valid sacrifice must go to the one sanctuary, all access to the Father goes through the one Mediator.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Speak to Aaron and his sons and to all the people — the double address (priestly and lay) of the blood legislation. Christ's sacrifice establishes the same universal standard: his blood is not a priestly prerogative but the universal atonement available to all: 'there is one God, and there is one mediator between God and men, the man Christ Jesus, who gave himself as a ransom for all' (1 Tim 2:5-6).</p>",
    "3": "<p>If any one of the house of Israel kills an ox or a lamb or a goat in the camp or outside the camp — all slaughter of these species anywhere must be brought to the sanctuary. The prohibition of unauthorized sacrifice reflects the principle that human beings cannot generate their own access to God; the sacrifice must come through the divinely appointed place and priest. Christ is 'the one mediator' precisely because all human attempts to approach God outside of his mediation are, in the type's language, unauthorized field slaughter to goat-demons.</p>",
    "4": "<p>And does not bring it to the entrance of the tent of meeting — bloodguilt for unauthorized sacrifice incurred as though human blood were shed. The severity — treating animal sacrifice outside the sanctuary as equivalent to murder — reflects that unauthorized appropriation of the atoning mechanism is a capital offense against the sovereignty of the one who appointed it. All human-devised 'atonement' outside of Christ's appointed sacrifice incurs the same kind of illegitimacy.</p>",
    "5": "<p>That the people may bring their sacrifices to YHWH at the entrance of the tent of meeting — the positive purpose of the centralization law: all sacrifice becomes a genuine encounter with YHWH rather than unauthorized deal-making with other powers. The gathering of all worship to the one sanctuary is the type of all worship gathered to the one risen Lord: 'in him all things hold together' (Col 1:17); 'all authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me' (Matt 28:18).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The priest shall throw the blood on the altar and burn the fat for a pleasing aroma to YHWH — the re-channeled field slaughter becomes legitimate peace offering with the standard blood-fat ritual. What was illegitimate outside becomes legitimate when brought to the appointed place and mediator. Christ's mediation transforms unauthorized human grasping into legitimate covenant approach: 'through him we both have access in one Spirit to the Father' (Eph 2:18).</p>",
    "7": "<p>No more sacrificing to the goat demons after whom they whore — the <em>se'irim</em> (goat-demons, wilderness spirits) represent all alternative spiritual authorities. Christ's cross disarms every competing spiritual power: 'he disarmed the rulers and authorities and put them to open shame, by triumphing over them in him' (Col 2:15). The prohibition on se'irim sacrifice is fulfilled in Christ's victory over the 'rulers and authorities' who are the NT counterpart to the se'irim of the wilderness.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Any one of the house of Israel or of the strangers who sojourns among them — the universal scope of the centralization law includes the resident Gentile. Christ's sacrifice is explicitly for all peoples: 'the Lamb who was slain' who 'ransomed people for God from every tribe and language and people and nation' (Rev 5:9). The inclusion of the sojourner in the blood legislation is the type of the inclusion of the Gentiles in the new covenant atonement.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Who offers a burnt offering or sacrifice and does not bring it to the entrance of the tent — karet for unauthorized sacrifice by Israelite or sojourner. The exclusivity of the one sanctuary prepares for the exclusivity of the one sacrifice. Christ is 'the stone the builders rejected' who has become 'the cornerstone' and about whom Peter declares: 'there is salvation in no one else, for there is no other name under heaven given among men by which we must be saved' (Acts 4:11-12).</p>",
    "10": "<p>If any one eats any blood, I will set my face against that person and will cut him off — the divine first-person threat against blood consumption. Yet Christ commands precisely this: 'unless you eat the flesh of the Son of Man and drink his blood, you have no life in you' (John 6:53). The apparent reversal is resolved by recognizing that the blood prohibition was in force precisely because blood was reserved for the atonement — and when Christ gives his blood as the final atonement, the 'drinking' of his blood is the receiving of that atoning gift. The prohibition protects the type until the antitype arrives and transforms the prohibition into invitation.</p>",
    "12": "<p>No person among you shall eat blood, and the stranger who sojourns among you shall not eat blood — the universal blood prohibition for all in Israel. The prohibition's universality is the mirror of the universal invitation in Christ: 'Come, everyone who thirsts, come to the waters' (Isa 55:1). The universal prohibition that guarded the blood-as-nefesh for the atonement becomes the universal invitation when the blood-as-nefesh of Christ is offered for all.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Any one who takes a beast or bird that may be eaten shall pour out its blood and cover it with earth — the earth-covering of game blood. Christ's blood was not merely shed but 'covered' — buried: 'I delivered to you as of first importance... that Christ died for our sins in accordance with the Scriptures, that he was buried' (1 Cor 15:3-4). The burial is an integral part of the atonement sequence, not merely a disposal; the earth that covered the game's blood is the type of the tomb that 'covered' the blood of the Lamb until the resurrection reversed the covering.</p>",
    "14": "<p>For the life of every creature is its blood: its blood is its life — the nefesh-blood identification restated for all creatures. The life of Christ — his divine-human nefesh — is uniquely present in his blood: 'This cup that is poured out for you is the new covenant in my blood' (Luke 22:20). The life of the Son of God poured out in death is the ultimate fulfillment of the nefesh-in-blood principle: the blood that atones does so precisely because it carries the infinite life of the eternal Son.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Whoever eats what died of itself or what was torn by beasts shall be unclean until evening — neveilah and terefah (animals that died without proper blood-draining) create impurity because the blood remained in them. The proper draining of blood at slaughter is the type of the proper 'pouring out' of Christ's blood in the sacrifice: 'he poured out his soul to death' (Isa 53:12, <em>heereh lammavet nafsho</em>). Christ is neither neveilah (died of itself) nor terefah (torn randomly) but the appointed sacrificial lamb whose blood was properly given at the appointed time.</p>",
    "16": "<p>If he does not wash them or bathe, he shall bear his iniquity — the purification requirement after eating improperly-bled meat. The principle that proximity to death (even animal death) requires purification points to the radical purification that proximity to Christ's death accomplishes: 'Do you not know that all of us who have been baptized into Christ Jesus were baptized into his death? We were buried therefore with him by baptism into death, in order that, just as Christ was raised from the dead by the glory of the Father, we too might walk in newness of life' (Rom 6:3-4). The laundering-and-bathing of the type becomes the baptismal dying-and-rising of the antitype.</p>"
  },
  "18": {
    "1": "<p>YHWH spoke to Moses — the opening revelation formula for the sexual prohibition code. The covenant framing of the entire chapter (Egypt/Canaan contrast, YHWH-self-identification) establishes that sexual ethics is a theological rather than merely social or biological matter. Christ's sexual ethics teaching maintains this covenant-theological grounding: 'Have you not read that he who created them from the beginning made them male and female, and said, &ldquo;Therefore a man shall leave his father and his mother and hold fast to his wife&rdquo;?' (Matt 19:4-5). The Creator's design is the ground of the ethics, not cultural convention.</p>",
    "2": "<p><em>Ani YHWH Eloheichem</em> — I am YHWH your God. The covenant-identity formula grounds the sexual ethics in who YHWH is, not merely in what he commands. Christ grounds his ethical teaching in the same way: 'I say to you' (Matt 5:22,28,32,34,39,44) — the 'you have heard it said' becomes 'but I say to you,' positioning his own authority as the new legislative basis, the fulfillment of the Mosaic legislation.</p>",
    "3": "<p>You shall not do as they do in the land of Egypt or as they do in the land of Canaan — the negative boundary-definition: Israel's ethics is not Egypt (slavery, law-without-grace) nor Canaan (freedom-without-law). Paul applies this same third-way logic to the church: 'you are not under law but under grace' (Rom 6:14-15) — not Egypt's servitude nor Canaan's license but the freedom of the sons of God who 'through the Spirit... put to death the deeds of the body' (Rom 8:13). Christ creates the third way that the Egypt/Canaan contrast could only gesture toward.</p>",
    "4": "<p>You shall follow my rules and keep my statutes and walk in them — the positive command after the negative boundary. Christ fulfills the positive command: 'Do not think that I have come to abolish the Law or the Prophets; I have not come to abolish them but to fulfill them' (Matt 5:17). He walks in the statutes perfectly, providing both the pattern of obedience and the atoning sacrifice for those who fail.</p>",
    "5": "<p><em>Va-chai bahem</em> — the person who does them shall live by them. This verse is Paul's key citation for the law-covenant in contrast to the faith-covenant: 'The one who does them shall live by them' (Gal 3:12, citing Lev 18:5 to show that the law operates on a doing-not-faith principle); and 'the righteousness based on the law... the person who does the commandments shall live by them' (Rom 10:5, contrasting with v.6's faith-righteousness). Christ fulfills Lev 18:5 by perfectly doing the commandments and thereby living — and then gives that life to those who have not done them, through faith rather than law-performance (Rom 10:9).</p>",
    "6": "<p>None of you shall approach any one of his close relatives to uncover nakedness — the foundational prohibition of the incest laws: <em>she'er basar</em> (flesh-kin) defines the protected zone of family relationships. Christ honors and protects these boundaries, establishing the family as the primary unit of society: 'Honor your father and mother' (Matt 15:4); his teaching defends both marital fidelity (Matt 5:27-32) and family obligations (Mark 7:9-13).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The nakedness of your father, which is the nakedness of your mother, you shall not uncover — the parent prohibition. Christ's deepest honoring of the parent-child boundary is in his own submission to Joseph and Mary: 'he went down with them and came to Nazareth and was submissive to them' (Luke 2:51); and his care for Mary from the cross: 'When Jesus saw his mother and the disciple whom he loved standing nearby, he said to his mother, &ldquo;Woman, behold, your son!&rdquo;' (John 19:26). He who is the Word incarnate submits to the family structure he created.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The nakedness of your father's wife — the stepmother prohibition, cited by Paul as the Corinthian violation: 'it is actually reported that there is sexual immorality among you, and of a kind that is not tolerated even among pagans, for a man has his father's wife' (1 Cor 5:1). Paul's appeal to the Levitical standard confirms that the sexual ethics of Lev 18 continues to govern the new covenant community's practice, even as the ceremonial and sacrificial law has been fulfilled and transformed.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The nakedness of your sister — the sibling prohibition. Christ establishes new family categories that transcend but do not replace biological family: 'Who are my mother and my brothers?... Whoever does the will of God, he is my brother and sister and mother' (Mark 3:33,35). The redefinition of family around covenant rather than biology does not dissolve the biological family's protective boundaries but situates them within the larger covenant community.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The nakedness of your son's daughter or of your daughter's daughter — the grandchild prohibition based on flesh-identity. The generational extension of kinship protection points to Christ's concern for children and the vulnerable: 'Let the little children come to me and do not hinder them' (Mark 10:14); 'Whoever causes one of these little ones who believe in me to sin, it would be better for him to have a great millstone fastened around his neck and to be drowned in the depth of the sea' (Matt 18:6). The protective framework for the most vulnerable family members is intensified, not relaxed, in Christ's teaching.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The nakedness of your father's wife's daughter — the stepsister prohibition based on relational (not biological) kinship. The equal weight of relational and biological kinship in the incest prohibitions confirms that family structures created by covenant (marriage) are as real as those created by birth. Christ honors covenant-created relationships: the church is his bride (Eph 5:25-27), created by covenant rather than biology, with all the full reality and obligation of the most intimate family bond.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The nakedness of your father's sister — the paternal aunt prohibition. The comprehensive coverage of extended family in the incest laws reflects the biblical understanding that the family is the fundamental social unit whose integrity must be protected at every generational level. Christ's coming does not dissolve these structures: 'do not think that I have come to abolish' (Matt 5:17) — the creational and covenantal family structures are not abolished but fulfilled and purified in the new creation.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The nakedness of your mother's sister — the maternal aunt prohibition, symmetrical with the paternal. The bilateral symmetry of the aunt prohibitions (paternal and maternal equally protected) reflects the equal dignity of both sides of the family structure. Christ's new covenant creates a bilateral covenant family: both Jew and Gentile, male and female, slave and free are equally included — 'there is neither Jew nor Greek, there is neither slave nor free, there is no male and female, for you are all one in Christ Jesus' (Gal 3:28).</p>",
    "14": "<p>The nakedness of your father's brother — the uncle relationship protected by extension. Paul uses family relationship language for the church: 'Do not rebuke an older man but encourage him as you would a father, younger men as brothers, older women as mothers, younger women as sisters, in all purity' (1 Tim 5:1-2). The family-relationship structure of Lev 18 is the template for the church's relational ethics: all the protective respect owed to family members is owed to fellow church members.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The nakedness of your daughter-in-law — the daughter-in-law prohibition. The family-by-marriage is as protected as the family-by-blood. Christ's treatment of the Samaritan woman (John 4) and the widow of Nain (Luke 7:11-15) shows the extension of covenant protection to women in vulnerable family positions (socially excluded, widowed). He honors and protects precisely those whom the family protection laws of Lev 18 were designed to cover.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The nakedness of your brother's wife — the brother's wife prohibition (with levirate exception). John the Baptist's rebuke of Herod Antipas for this violation (Mark 6:17-18) shows that the Lev 18 sexual ethics were applied in NT prophetic ministry as the binding standard for covenant behavior. John's willingness to die for this rebuke (Mark 6:27-28) confirms that the sexual ethics of the Holiness Code were not understood as merely Mosaic legislation superseded by the new covenant but as creational-covenantal standards whose prophetic enforcement was continuous.</p>",
    "17": "<p>A woman and her daughter — the three-generation prohibition of simultaneous relationships with a woman and her daughter/granddaughter. The most severe penalty in Lev 20:14 (burning) matches the severity of the term here: <em>zimmah</em> (deliberate depravity). Christ's eschatological judgment language reserves its most severe imagery for those who harm the most vulnerable: 'it would be better for him to have a great millstone fastened around his neck and to be drowned' (Matt 18:6) — the triple-generation violation that exploits the structures of family trust deserves the triple-generation's protective curse.</p>",
    "18": "<p>A woman as a rival wife to her sister — the rival-sisters prohibition. Christ resolves the tensions created by the polygamy that the Levitical legislation regulated without endorsing: 'from the beginning it was not so' (Matt 19:8), appealing to the creation norm (Gen 2:24) as the standard that the Mosaic legislation partially accommodated but did not establish. Christ returns the marriage ethics to its pre-fallen standard.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Do not approach a woman in her menstrual uncleanness — the niddah prohibition. The woman with a twelve-year flow of blood (Mark 5:25-34) — living under continuous niddah impurity — approaches Christ and is healed; he declares her healed and at peace rather than rebuking the touch. Christ does not abolish the niddah legislation but fulfills its trajectory: his healing of her chronic discharge demonstrates his power over the very category of impurity the legislation addressed.</p>",
    "20": "<p>You shall not lie with your neighbor's wife — the adultery prohibition. Christ intensifies this: 'everyone who looks at a woman with lustful intent has already committed adultery with her in his heart' (Matt 5:28). The Levitical prohibition of the outward act is brought to bear on the inward disposition; Christ applies the law at its deepest level, fulfilling rather than relaxing the marital-covenant protection of Lev 18:20.</p>",
    "21": "<p>You shall not give any of your children to Molech — child sacrifice in the heart of the sexual prohibition chapter. Christ's protection of children is the antitype of the Molech prohibition: 'Let the children come to me; do not hinder them, for to such belongs the kingdom of God' (Mark 10:14). The same passage where Christ blesses children (Mark 10:13-16) contrasts directly with the Molech sacrifice of children: one is the perversion of parenthood (giving children to death), the other its fulfillment (bringing children to the living God).</p>",
    "22": "<p>You shall not lie with a male as with a woman — the prohibition placed in the list of violations that are to'evah (abomination) to YHWH. Paul's treatment in Rom 1:26-27 situates this prohibition within the broader framework of creation-order violations that result from suppressing the truth of God: 'they exchanged natural relations for those that are contrary to nature.' The to'evah category of Lev 18 is applied in the new covenant not as a ceremonial violation but as a creation-order deviation addressed through the gospel's transforming power.</p>",
    "23": "<p>You shall not lie with any animal — the bestiality prohibition; <em>tevel</em> (confusion of kinds, species-boundary violation). The creation order that the bestiality prohibition protects ('every creature according to its kind,' Gen 1) is the same creation order that Christ's parousia will restore: 'the creation itself will be set free from its bondage to corruption and obtain the freedom of the glory of the children of God' (Rom 8:21). The tevel that violated created categories will be reversed when all creation is renewed in Christ.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Do not make yourselves unclean by any of these things — the closing frame: the nations were expelled for these violations. Christ gathers from all nations the 'clean' community — not those who never violated these laws but those who have been washed: 'But you were washed, you were sanctified, you were justified in the name of the Lord Jesus Christ' (1 Cor 6:11). The nations' expulsion through defilement is answered by the nations' gathering through purification in Christ.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The land became unclean, so I punished its iniquity upon it, and the land vomited out its inhabitants — <em>vataqe ha-aretz et-yoshveiha</em>. Christ bears the land's vomiting upon himself: he is executed outside the city (the land vomits him out), cursed on the tree (Gal 3:13: 'Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us — for it is written, &ldquo;Cursed is everyone who is hanged on a tree&rdquo;'), and buried in the earth that had vomited its inhabitants. He enters the curse-trajectory of the land to reverse it from within.</p>",
    "26": "<p>You shall keep my statutes and my rules and do none of these abominations, either the native or the stranger — the universal covenant standard for all who live in the land. In Christ, the sojourner-Gentile and the native-Israelite are equally incorporated into the covenant people: 'he himself is our peace, who has made us both one and has broken down in his flesh the dividing wall of hostility' (Eph 2:14). The equal application of the Holiness Code to native and sojourner is fulfilled in the equal membership of Jew and Gentile in the one body of Christ.</p>",
    "27": "<p>For the people of the land who were before you did all of these abominations — the Canaanite violations are the historical ground for the expulsion. Christ does not dismiss this history but recapitulates it in reverse: where Canaan's sin produced expulsion, his bearing of all human sin (including Canaan's) in the cross turns expulsion into restoration. 'In Christ God was reconciling the world to himself, not counting their trespasses against them' (2 Cor 5:19) — the world's Canaanite-magnitude sin is not held against those in Christ.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Lest the land vomit you out when you make it unclean, as it vomited out the nation that was before you — the warning applied to Israel: the same covenant principle that expelled Canaan will expel Israel if they follow the same path. History confirmed this (the Babylonian exile). Christ absorbs the land-vomiting curse so that his people will not be vomited out: 'whoever feeds on my flesh and drinks my blood abides in me, and I in him' (John 6:56). To abide in Christ is to be kept in the land; to be ejected from Christ is the only true exile.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Everyone who does any of these abominations shall be cut off from among his people — karet for the entire violation-list. Christ's death is the ultimate karet — cut off from the land of the living (Isa 53:8: <em>nigzar me-eretz hayyim</em>, cut off from the land of the living) — borne in the place of those who deserved the cutting off. 'The punishment that brought us peace was on him, and by his wounds we are healed' (Isa 53:5) — the karet that belonged to the violators falls on the one who bore their violations.</p>",
    "30": "<p><em>Ani YHWH</em> — the final covenant self-identification closes the chapter where it began. The chapter's architecture (v.2: <em>ani YHWH Eloheichem</em>; v.30: <em>ani YHWH</em>) frames all the sexual ethics within the divine identity. Christ's closing statement in the Sermon on the Mount mirrors this: 'everyone then who hears these words of mine and does them will be like a wise man who built his house on the rock' (Matt 7:24). The divine-identity ground of Lev 18's ethics is fulfilled in the 'I say to you' authority of the one who is 'greater than the temple' (Matt 12:6) and 'Lord of the Sabbath' (Matt 12:8).</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    e = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'leviticus')
    merge_comm(e, DATA)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'leviticus', e)
    print('Leviticus 16-18 mkt-christ written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
